      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about how bread gets that nice brown color on the crust and i think it's called the maillard reaction? can u explain how that actually works and what temps i need to look out for so i dont burn everything?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a complex chemical process that gives bread its lovely brown crust, which is essentially a series of browning reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars. It's not just one thing, but a cascade that produces hundreds of flavorful compounds. You'll see this happen when the surface temperature of the bread reaches about 285°F (140°C) or higher, which is when the sugars and proteins start to react vigorously. If the heat is too high too fast, you risk burning the crust before the inside is cooked through.",
